rrent preoccupations in scholarship and perennial concerns, and use both traditional and new methodologies to study a variety of texts. Topics covered include ideologies of love and courtliness; women's voices and roles; incest and identity; poetics; historical approaches; and adaptations and transformations. First delivered at the 1998 meeting of the International Courtly Literature Society at Vancouver, the articles demonstrate the vitality of the field andoffer fresh new insights into the tradition of courtly literature as a whole.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aCourtly love in literaturevCongresses. 0aKings and rulers in literaturevCongresses. 0aLiterature, MedievalvCongressesxHistory and criticism. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh1 aAllen, Rosamund S, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllen, Rosamund, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAltmann, Barbara K, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAyers, Pat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBertolucci Pizzorusso, Valeria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlue, Walter A, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlue, Walter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBossy, Michel-André, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrault, Gerard J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrault, Gerard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrodovitch, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrumlik, Joan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuschinger, Danielle, 